<table class="infobox vcard" style="width:22em">
 <caption style="font-style:italic;padding-bottom:0.2em;">
  Theatrum Orbis Terrarum
 </caption>
 <tr>
  <td colspan="2" style="text-align:center">
   <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:OrteliusWorldMap1570.jpg">
    <img alt="OrteliusWorldMap1570.jpg" data-file-height="3961" data-file-width="5816" height="272" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/OrteliusWorldMap1570.jpg/400px-OrteliusWorldMap1570.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/OrteliusWorldMap1570.jpg/600px-OrteliusWorldMap1570.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/OrteliusWorldMap1570.jpg/800px-OrteliusWorldMap1570.jpg 2x" width="400"/>
   </a>
   <div>
    In 1570 (May 20) Gilles Coppens de Diest at Antwerp published 53 maps created by
    <a href="/wiki/Abraham_Ortelius" title="Abraham Ortelius">
     Abraham Ortelius
    </a>
    under the title
    <i>
     Theatrum Orbis Terrarum
    </i>
    , considered the "first modern atlas".
    <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2">
     <a href="#cite_note-2">
      [Note 1]
     </a>
    </sup>
    Three
    <a href="/wiki/Latin" title="Latin">
     Latin
    </a>
    editions of this (besides a
    <a href="/wiki/Dutch_language" title="Dutch language">
     Dutch
    </a>
    , a French and a
    <a href="/wiki/German_language" title="German language">
     German
    </a>
    edition) appeared before the end of 1572; twenty-five editions came out before Ortelius' death in 1598; and several others were published subsequently, for the atlas continued to be in demand till about 1612. This is the world map from this atlas.
   </div>
  </td>
 </tr>
